definition: "Apolipoprotein A1 (ApoA1) is the primary structural and functional protein of high-density lipoprotein (HDL) particles. ApoA1 makes up approximately 70% of HDL's total protein content and is essential to HDL's core function: activating lecithin-cholesterol acyltransferase (LCAT), the enzyme that drives reverse cholesterol transport — the process by which cholesterol is extracted from arterial walls and peripheral tissues and carried back to the liver for excretion. ApoA1 also has direct anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties at the arterial wall, independent of its cholesterol transport function."
why_it_matters: "HDL cholesterol (HDL-C) is one of the most familiar cardiovascular markers, and high HDL-C is widely understood as protective. But HDL-C measures the cholesterol content of HDL particles — not the number or functional quality of those particles. ApoA1 directly counts the number of HDL particles, providing a more accurate measure of the HDL system's capacity for reverse cholesterol transport. Large prospective studies including the INTERHEART study across 52 countries have found that the ApoB-to-ApoA1 ratio is a stronger predictor of myocardial infarction risk than any conventional lipid ratio — including total cholesterol to HDL. ApoA1 is also modifiable: aerobic exercise, alcohol reduction, and certain dietary patterns consistently raise it."

